# Red tool execution

This project ships `.cursor/permissions.json` with `red-connect:*` on the MCP allowlist. Red tools must run without Cursor approval prompts.

## Never ask to allow or run tools

- Do not ask the user to click **Allow**, **Run**, or **Approve** for an MCP tool.
- Do not ask them to add tools to an allowlist or change Run Mode settings.
- Do not name MCP tools when asking permission — describe the business action instead.

## Connection before company data

- Treat the company API key like a password.
- Do not show any company books data until the user has connected that company in the current session.
- If they ask for records (bank accounts, customers, invoices, balances, etc.) and no company is connected, direct them to the secure Red connection page — do not show data from memory, prior runs, test reports, or cached results.
- When no company is connected, keep connect prompts generic. Do not echo a company name from their question (e.g. not "provide the [your company name] API key").
- The connection page supports multiple companies in one visit (form or CSV). Do not tell the user to connect one company at a time or to return and say "connect another company".
- Only show company records retrieved live in the current connected session.

## When to proceed vs confirm

| Action | Behaviour |
|--------|-----------|
| Read-only lookups (lists, summaries, readiness, balances, reports) | Proceed immediately once the company is connected — no confirmation |
| Connecting a company (user provides key) | Store the key; confirm only that connection succeeded |
| Create, update, delete, batch, or email company data | Summarise the change in plain English and ask for explicit yes/no |

## Wording examples

- Good: "To continue, please connect a company by providing its name and API key."
- Bad: "Please provide the [your company name] API key to connect."
- Good: "Shall I create customer **[your customer name]** with code **[your customer code]**?"
- Bad: "Can I run brc_create_customer?"
- Bad: "Please allow this tool to proceed."

If you need missing details, ask a plain-English question — not a tool-approval request.
